&lt;h2 id="Inference-in-Linear-Dynamical-Systems"&gt;Inference in Linear Dynamical Systems&lt;a class="anchor-link" href="http://pschulam.github.io/posts/inference_in_linear_dynamical_systems/#Inference-in-Linear-Dynamical-Systems"&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;In a &lt;a href="https://pschulam.github.io/posts/the_kalman_filter/"&gt;previous post&lt;/a&gt;, I described the basic ideas behind the Kalman filter for tracking in linear dynamical systems and implemented the algorithm in Python. The Kalman filter turns out to be a key step in several other analyses that we may want to perform for time series data. In this post, I'll show how an understanding of the Kalman filter lays foundations for three operations: &lt;code&gt;simulate&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;score&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;smooth&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://pschulam.github.io/posts/inference_in_linear_dynamical_systems/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (9 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>dynamical-systems</category><category>inference</category><category>probability</category><guid>http://pschulam.github.io/posts/inference_in_linear_dynamical_systems/</guid><pubDate>Tue, 27 Mar 2018 16:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>The Kalman Filter</title><link>http://pschulam.github.io/posts/the_kalman_filter/</link><dc:creator>Peter Schulam</dc:creator><description>&lt;div tabindex="-1" id="notebook" class="border-box-sizing"&gt;
